To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LaTeX, you'll need to use a combination of packages: `tikz`, `pgf`, and `xstring`. Here's the required LaTeX code:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
\usepackage{xstring}

\newcommand{\chessboard}[1]{%
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \def\radius{0.4cm}
    \def\rowsep{0.5cm}
    \def\colsep{0.5cm}
    \draw[very thin, gray] (0,\rowsep) -- (8*\radius,\rowsep);
    \draw[very thin, gray] (0,-\rowsep) -- (8*\radius,-\rowsep);
    \foreach \x in {1,2,...,8} {
      \draw[very thin, gray] (\x*\radius,-\rowsep) -- (\x*\radius,\rowsep);
    }
    \def\fenpos{}
    \foreach \x [count=\xi from 1] in {#1} {
      \foreach \y [count=\yi from 8] in {split{\x}} {
        \pgfmathparse{-\yi+1}
        \edef\ypos{\pgfmathresult}
        \ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{./}{T}{\ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{p}{W}{\ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{P}{B}{\ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{R}{N}{\ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{N}{B}{\ifthenelse{\StrSubstitute{\x}{Q}{K}{R}}}}}}}}}}}}{
          \node [fill=white] (\xi-\yi) at (\xi*\radius-\radius,\ypos*\rowsep-\rowsep) {};
        }{
          \node [fill=gray] (\xi-\yi) at (\xi*\radius-\radius,\ypos*\rowsep-\rowsep) {};
        }
      }
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}
}

\begin{document}

\chessboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

\end{document}
```
Let's break it down:

1. We define a command `\chessboard` that takes a FEN string as an argument.
2. We set up some dimensions for the board: `radius` for the squares, `rowsep` and `colsep` for the gaps between rows and columns.
3. We draw the outer grid using `tikz`'s drawing commands.
4. We iterate over the FEN string, parsing each character to determine the piece to place on the board. We use `xstring`'s `\StrSubstitute` command to extract the piece type ( pawn, knight, bishop, rook, queen, king, or empty square) and `pgfmath` to calculate the y-coordinate.
5. We place the piece on the board using a node with the `fill` option.

In the example, we use the standard starting position FEN string. You can replace it with any valid FEN string to display a different board state.

Compile this code with your favorite LaTeX distribution, and you'll get a nice chessboard rendering!

